WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.020
I'm going to talk about post-transplant therapy with ibertamide and daratumumab.

00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:07.220
These are my disclosures.

00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:17.440
And just to review, ibertamide is a member of a new class of immunomodulatory drugs called

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:23.060
CellMods, targeting the cereblon-E3 ligase complex.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.580
Normally, this is a normal part of protein degradation.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:36.540
And in the absence of IMIDs or CellMods, there's a certain cache of client proteins,

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:41.260
substrates that get dragged to the proteasome and degraded.

00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:50.020
And in the presence of IMIDs or CellMods, there's a change in the substrate profile

00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:57.540
that's bound, which includes icorose and aolose, which are, as we know, important plasma cell

00:00:57.540 --> 00:00:58.260
survival proteins.

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:06.280
And the relative degree to which these survival proteins can be degraded are significantly

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:11.980
higher with the CellMods than with IMIDs.

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:19.220
And iber, for instance, compared to lenalidomide and pomalidomide, about 20 times more so.

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:27.200
So this has been not just shown preclinically, but we know that this translates into clinical

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:27.740
activity.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:34.140
And that about a third of IMID refractory patients can respond to the combination of

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:35.540
iberdomide and dexamethasone.

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:39.420
And we're going to hear in the next talk, I'm not going to go through this slide, but

00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:46.840
we're going to hear about a talk comparing iberdomide to lenalidomide directly as post-transplant

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:48.000
maintenance therapy.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:57.200
I'm, I just want to also just further, like, the rationale for including daratumumab in

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:57.880
the drug.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:02.640
And I think the rationale for including daratumumab as part of the combination has to do with

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:09.520
the immune modulation that these drugs promote their activity on T cells and NK cell activation

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:15.720
and expansion directly feeds into the, the, the mechanistic activity of daratumumab.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:21.320
And so there, there is strong rationale for combining these agents together.

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:26.660
So we are in the midst of doing a study called the IBEX trial at the U.S. Department of Health.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:33.920
At the Kermanos Cancer Institute with our friends and colleagues at Indiana University, this

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:41.360
is using iberdomide and daratumumab as post-transplant maintenance in patients who have had

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.180
daratumumab containing induction therapy prior to transplant.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.720
Originally, the study, the primary endpoint of this study was conversion from MRD positivity

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:56.060
to MRD negativity.

00:02:56.060 --> 00:03:02.660
So the original patients enrolled were all MRD positive at the end of transplants.

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:08.560
We modified the, you know, as our, as our thinking about best use and most, you know,

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:11.200
informative MRD results has evolved.

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:18.180
We changed the primary endpoint to sustained MRD negativity, which no longer requires the

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:20.120
patients to be MRD positive at enrollment.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:24.120
And so currently we're taking all comers as long as they've been DARA exposed.

00:03:25.460 --> 00:03:32.060
The starting dose of iberdomide is 0.75 milligrams daily for 21 out of every 28 days.

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:37.500
And the daratumumab schedule in this study was designed intentionally to very closely

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:44.580
mimic the DARA schedule of the dramatic study because I think many of us are anticipating

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:52.240
that after the dramatic study results come out that lenalidomide and daratumumab may be

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:55.120
the standard to which future maintenance is compared, right?

00:03:55.460 --> 00:04:02.480
Another key endpoint of this study is safety and the design of the safety analysis is such

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:10.500
that it will permit us to report on some interim results, including safety at ASH this year

00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:16.920
and spoiler alert, as you might guess, neutropenia and, you know, myelosuppression is the main

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:21.260
thing that we're seeing early on, especially during the more intensive part of the DARA

00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:21.840
dosing.

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:25.440
And ultimately we'll be doing some immune profiling as well.

00:04:25.460 --> 00:04:33.640
This is not the only study looking at iberdomide in combination with CD38 antibodies as maintenance

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:38.600
therapy yesterday or a couple of days ago, we heard about the MIDAS study, which in patients

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:45.500
who are MRD positive included iber-ISA maintenance following transplants.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:55.440
We also have another study comparing RVD, ISA-RVD and ISA-Iberdomide.

00:04:55.460 --> 00:05:05.280
And I think those are both a way out in terms of hearing, you know, any real information

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:10.220
about the results of the maintenance strategy, but we probably will be hearing something

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:17.180
at ASH this year from our friends in the commit consortium, which did this phase two study.

00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:19.700
This picture makes it look like it's a randomized study.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:25.380
It's really a two cohort study of iber, DARA.

00:05:25.460 --> 00:05:33.100
It's a post-transplant consolidation versus iber, DARA, Kyprolis post-transplant consolidation,

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.360
followed by iber maintenance as a single agent.

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:43.280
And the primary endpoint of this study is also conversion from MRD positivity to MRD

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:45.760
negativity at six months.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:52.360
So we will hear about that particular endpoint at ASH this year.

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:53.280
One interesting, I think, thing about this study is that, you know, we'll be hearing

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:53.280
a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:53.280
We'll be hearing a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:53.280
We'll be hearing a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:53.280
We'll be hearing a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:53.320
We'll be hearing a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:53.360
We'll be hearing a lot more about this study in the next couple of weeks.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:06:02.440
But I think the thing about this study is that DARA or CD38 antibody exposure as part

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:04.540
of induction is permitted but not required.

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:10.640
And so my feeling is it may be a little bit difficult to know what this combination is

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:15.880
adding to what we would consider best induction if it turns out, I don't know the answer to

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:20.120
this, we're not part of this consortium, but if a significant number of patients were

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:23.340
not DARA exposed during induction, you're going to see extraordinary results.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:35.200
And so my parting thoughts in the last 25 seconds, we know that this is a more potent

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:42.820
cereblon targeting agent than IMIDs, and we're going to learn about these drugs in direct

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:43.960
comparison to IMIDs.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:52.860
There is currently, at the FDA, they're currently reviewing the data on Iber, DARA, Dex based

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:53.060
on the Iber, DARA, Dex.

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:53.080
And so we're going to learn about these drugs in direct comparison to IMIDs.

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:53.140
And so my parting thoughts in the last 25 seconds, we know that this is a more potent

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:58.440
the Excalibur relapsed refractory myeloma study. So this actually may be an approved combination

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:06.120
by the time we have final results from this study. We'll hear about preliminary results at ASH this

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:10.140
year. And then the big question I think that, I mean, most of us are probably wondering after

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:15.960
hearing about all of this, you know, bispecific and CAR-T data is, you know, is this, how relevant

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:22.740
is this going to be in an era when we're now moving towards things like BCMA bispecifics

00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:31.740
in combination with the CD38? Can this kind of a combination be relevant in that era? And I would

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:36.240
say, you know, if you can't beat it, maybe join it. There is also mechanistic, you know, reason

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:42.220
to think that ibertamide may help Bispecific activity as well. And that may be the

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:47.300
future path for maintenance therapy with cell mods. That's it. Thanks.
